\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Compact Lie Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
BASICS OF TOPOLOGICAL GROUPS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First definitions and examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
topological group 
\series default
is a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with a group structure such that the multiplication map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m:G\times G\to G
\]

\end_inset

and inversion map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i:G\to G
\]

\end_inset

are continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g}:G\to G$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g}(g')=gg'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in G$
\end_inset

, denote the left multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 This is because we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g}$
\end_inset

 as a composition of continuous maps 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=50] G 
\backslash
arrow[r,"g' 
\backslash
mapsto (g 
\backslash
text{,}g') "] & G 
\backslash
times G 
\backslash
arrow[r,"(g 
\backslash
text{,} g') 
\backslash
mapsto gg' "]  & G.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The open subset
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{GL}_{n}(\mathbb{R})\subset\text{Mat}_{n}(\mathbb{R})
\]

\end_inset

can be given the structure of a topological group via the usual multiplication
 and inversion of matrices.
 We topologize it with the subspace topology (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Mat}_{n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 given the Euclidean topology as a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space).
 Matrix multiplication is given in terms of polynomials, and similarly for
 inversion with rational functions whose denominator is a power of the determina
nt (Cramer's Formula).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

 be topological groups.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\times G'$
\end_inset

 is a topological group.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
Lie group 
\series default
is a topological group with a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold structure such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m:G\times G\to G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota:G\to G$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a complex vector space.
 A 
\series bold
hermitian form 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $h:V\times V\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 that is sesquiliner and conjugate-symmetric.
 atisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v,w)=\overline{h(w,v)}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h:V\times V\to\mathbb{C}
\]

\end_inset

that is sesquiliner and satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v,w)=\overline{h(w,v)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
By sesquilinear, we mean for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},b_{1},b_{2}\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2},w_{1},w_{2}\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2},b_{1}w_{1}+b_{2}w_{2})=a_{1}\overline{b}_{1}h(v_{1},w_{1})+a_{1}\overline{b}_{1}h(v_{1},w_{2})+a_{2}\overline{b}_{1}h(v_{2},w_{1})+a_{2}\overline{b}_{2}h(v_{2},w_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

By conjugate-symmetric, we mean for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(v,w)=\overline{h(w,v)}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 hermitian form the be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle v,w\rangle_{\text{std}}=\sum_{j}v_{j}\overline{w}_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

This particular hermitian form is also 
\series bold
non-degenerate
\series default
, meaning that the conjugate-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to V^{*}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $w\mapsto h(\cdot,w)$
\end_inset

, is an isomorphism (equivalently injective, by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-dimension reasons).
 Equivalently, if 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v,w)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $w=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As a consequence of the conjugate-symmetry, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v,v)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 be a non-degenerate hermitian form on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(h):=\left\{ g\in\text{GL}(V)\mid h(gv,gw)=h(v,w)\text{ for all }v,w\in V\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
non-degenerate
\emph default
, it is easy to check that any 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\text{End}(V)$
\end_inset

 preserving 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in this way has trivial kernel and so is automatically in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\text{Ker}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =h(gv,0)\\
 & =h(gv,gw)\\
 & =h(v,w),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $w=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus, the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $U(h)$
\end_inset

 is unaffected by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}(V)$
\end_inset

, ensuring that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(h)$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}(V)$
\end_inset

 and not just closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

